Summary: This section explains how to access and utilize the depth texture in Godot shaders to reconstruct world positions.

To read from the depth texture, define a uniform sampler2D with the hint ``hint_depth_texture``.
GDScript:
uniform sampler2D depth_texture : hint_depth_texture;

The depth texture can then be sampled using the ``texture()`` function.
GDScript:
float depth = texture(depth_texture, SCREEN_UV).x;

Note: Accessing the depth texture is restricted to the current viewport.

The depth values from ``depth_texture`` range from 1.0 (near plane) to 0.0 (far plane) due to reverse-z buffering and are nonlinear. Direct display appears mostly black. To align depth with world coordinates, linearization is required. This involves transforming screen-space coordinates to Normalized Device Coordinates (NDC) and then using the inverse projection matrix.

NDC coordinates range from -1.0 to 1.0 for x and y. For Vulkan renderers (Forward+, Mobile), z ranges from 0.0 to 1.0. For the Compatibility renderer (OpenGL), z ranges from -1.0 to 1.0.

GDScript:
void fragment() {
  float depth = texture(depth_texture, SCREEN_UV).x;
  // For Vulkan renderers (Forward+, Mobile)
  vec3 ndc = vec3(SCREEN_UV * 2.0 - 1.0, depth);
}

Note: For the Compatibility renderer, use:
GDScript:
vec3 ndc = vec3(SCREEN_UV, depth) * 2.0 - 1.0;

To ensure compatibility across all renderers:
GDScript:
#if CURRENT_RENDERER == RENDERER_COMPATIBILITY
vec3 ndc = vec3(SCREEN_UV, depth) * 2.0 - 1.0;
#else
vec3 ndc = vec3(SCREEN_UV * 2.0 - 1.0, depth);
#endif

Convert NDC to view space by multiplying with ``INV_PROJECTION_MATRIX``. The z-value in view space represents the distance to the point.
GDScript:
void fragment() {
  ...
  vec4 view = INV_PROJECTION_MATRIX * vec4(ndc, 1.0);
  view.xyz /= view.w;
  float linear_depth = -view.z; // Negate view.z as camera faces negative z
}

To reconstruct the world position, transform the view-space position into world space using ``INV_VIEW_MATRIX``.
GDScript:
void fragment() {
  ...
  vec4 world = INV_VIEW_MATRIX * INV_PROJECTION_MATRIX * vec4(ndc, 1.0);
  vec3 world_position = world.xyz / world.w;
}
